 initial volume in the series was dedicated to epistemology, the philosophy of science, and the philosophy of nature, while the second dealt with issues of value theory, ethics, and practical philosophy. In Volume III Rescher examines the nature of philosophical inquiry itself, seeking to affirm the classical conception of philosophy as a significant problem-solving enterprise that draws on the whole range of human experience to attempt to resolve the "big questions."Originally published in 1994.The Princeton Legacy Library uses the latest print-on-demand technology to again make available previously out-of-print books from the distinguished backlist of Princeton University Press. These editions preserve the original texts of these important books while presenting them in durable paperback and hardcover editions. The goal of the Princeton Legacy Library is to vastly increase access to the rich scholarly heritage found in the thousands of books published by Princeton University Press since its founding in 1905.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aIdealism. 0aPragmatism. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton Legacy Lib. eBook Package 1980-1999z978311041344108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton Legacy Lib. eBook Package Philosophyz978311041356408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140086383940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400863839423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400863839.jpg  a978-3-11-041344-1  Princeton Legacy Lib. eBook Package 1980-1999c1980d1999  a978-3-11-041356-4  Princeton Legacy Lib. eBook Package Philosophy  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Pack